  "response": "Okay, here’s a personalized meal plan designed for you, taking into account your profile and specific needs, delivered with expert sports nutrition guidance. This focuses on weight loss while managing PCOS and accommodating your preferences & restrictions. \n\n**Important Disclaimer:** *This is a sample meal plan based on the information provided. It's crucial to monitor your progress, listen to your body, and consult with your doctor or a registered dietitian for ongoing adjustments, especially given your PCOS diagnosis.*\n\n\n---\n\n**Personalized Meal Plan – Maharashtra (Female, 35)**\n\n**Daily Calorie Target:** 1600\n**Protein Target:** 110g\n\n\n\n**Breakfast (Approx. Calories: 320 | Approx. Protein: 30g)**\n\n*   **Meal:**  Upma with Vegetables & Nuts \n    *   *Recipe:*  1 cup semolina (rava) cooked in water with diced vegetables like carrots, peas, and bell peppers (approx. ½ cup total). Season with mustard seeds, turmeric powder, chopped green chilies, curry leaves – all staples in Maharashtra cuisine. Add a small handful of almonds & cashews for healthy fats and extra protein.\n*   **Reasoning:** Upma is a traditional Maharashtrian breakfast that’s naturally low-calorie and high in fiber. Vegetables add nutrients and volume. Nuts contribute healthy fats and some protein, helping with satiety. The spices also help regulate blood sugar levels.\n\n\n**Morning Snack (Approx. Calories: 180 | Approx. Protein: 20g)**\n\n*   **Meal:**  Sprouts Salad with Lemon & Coriander\n    * *Recipe:* 1 cup sprouted moong or chana sprouts mixed with chopped cucumber, tomato, onion and a squeeze of lemon juice. Sprinkle generously with fresh coriander leaves (cilantro).\n*   **Reasoning:** Sprouts are packed with protein and enzymes, aiding digestion. Lemon helps alkalize the body and can aid in PCOS symptom management.  This is a refreshing and easy-to-digest option – vital given your PCOS.\n\n\n**Lunch (Approx. Calories: 450 | Approx. Protein: 35g)**\n\n*   **Meal:** Chicken Curry with Brown Rice & Mixed Vegetables\n    *   *Recipe:* 120 g of chicken pieces cooked in a moderate amount of onion, ginger-garlic paste, turmeric, cumin, coriander powder and chili powder (avoiding excessive oil). Serve alongside ½ cup brown rice (a more complex carbohydrate for sustained energy) and 1 cup of mixed vegetable curry (seasonal vegetables like eggplant, okra, beans – common in Maharashtra).\n*   **Reasoning:** Lean protein from chicken is key for muscle maintenance. Brown rice provides fiber to control blood sugar.  The combination of vegetables and spices offers a range of vitamins & minerals beneficial for PCOS management. Chicken also contains Choline that supports liver health which can be affected by PCOS.\n\n\n**Evening Snack (Approx. Calories: 150 | Approx. Protein: 20g)**\n\n*   **Meal:** Roasted Chickpeas with Spices\n    * *Recipe:* 1 cup of roasted chickpeas seasoned with cumin seeds, turmeric powder, chili powder and a pinch of salt.  Roasting enhances flavor and texture.\n*   **Reasoning:**  Chickpeas are an excellent source of protein and fiber – essential for curbing cravings and stabilizing blood sugar after dinner.\n\n\n\n**Dinner (Approx. Calories: 320 | Approx. Protein: 35g)**\n\n*   **Meal:** Fish Curry with Roti & Salad\n     * *Recipe:* 120 g fish (like Pomfret or Rohu – available in Maharashtra) cooked in a coconut milk-based curry (use light coconut milk).  Serve with two whole wheat rotis and a simple salad of lettuce, cucumber and tomato.\n*   **Reasoning:** Fish is rich in Omega-3 fatty acids, which have anti-inflammatory properties that can be beneficial for PCOS symptoms. Whole wheat roti provides complex carbohydrates.  The fish curry will provide essential nutrients without adding excessive fat.\n\n\n**Important Notes & Considerations (Specifically Addressing Your Needs):**\n\n*   **PCOS Management:** This plan focuses on foods with a low glycemic index to minimize insulin spikes – a key factor in managing PCOS. High fiber intake from vegetables, brown rice, and sprouts helps regulate blood sugar levels.  Lean protein at every meal is also crucial for insulin sensitivity.\n*   **Lactose Intolerance:** Absolutely no dairy products are included. Plant-based alternatives like almond/soy milk can be added to curries (used sparingly) if desired but avoid adding creamy ingredients.\n*   **Maharashtra Specific Foods:** The plan incorporates widely available Maharashtrian staples like *rava*, spices, lentils, and common seafood. \n*   **Muscle Mass Building (Below Average):** While this is a weight loss-focused plan, the higher protein intake (110g) aims to support some muscle building alongside fat loss – especially when combined with your 3 workout days per week.\n*   **Hydration:** Drink plenty of water throughout the day (at least 8 glasses).\n\n---\n\nTo help me refine this further, could you tell me:\n\n*   Are there any particular spices you enjoy or dislike?\n*   What kind of vegetables are most readily available and affordable in your area of Maharashtra?\n*   Would you like to explore some alternative protein sources (e.g., eggs)?",
